#### Integration Points

Basically when your system depends on interfacing or receiving data from another system. Integrations happen in the following ways, and have the following ways in which they can go bad.

##### Socket-based protocols

* If working directly with sockets, be aware that connections may take (very) long to accept and establish a working connection. Quick refusals are far better than waiting forever, which can happen if you do not have timeouts in place. Be sure to watch socket connection values from whatever API you're using.
* Synchronous connections always have the potential to block threads, make sure your UI won't lock up because of this.

##### "The 5AM Problem" - Working against locked connections, firewalls, and TCP/IP

* The author presents an anecdote where he solved a site locking issue that involved connections that were for all intensive purposes dead and should have been closed, but because of interactions with firewalls and OS level socket timeout (which are very long) were kept open and unresponsive.
* The solution involved setting up what was basically heartbeat pinging to clients at some interval, so live clients would reply to the ping, dead ones wouldn't, and the firewall's "last packet" time would be reset, keeping everything orderly.

##### Http Protocols

* Using protocols such as SOAP, XML-RPC, REST and using http clients
* The same blocking and timeout problems with socket-based protocols happen here, since HTTP travels over sockets.
* Need to account for endpoint security

##### Vendor API Libraries

* Relying on libraries that are not open can mean having to rely on buggy, vulnerable, or just plain bad code that you don't control. Furthermore, reported issues may take forever to fix.
* Could contain blocking code also, so be aware of performance changes.

##### Countering these problems

* Make your systems more robust using Circuit Breakers, decoupling middleware, and writing test harnesses for components that spit all kinds of nastiness at your system, and can impose load.
* Packet sniffers and other network monitoring can be your best friend when things get hairy. Digging into what is happening below the surface can be very revealing.

#### Chain Reactions

* When one worker (server, thread, connection, etc) goes down, is blocked, or experiences failure, the remaining workers must work harder to pick up the difference. This increased load can expaserbate latent problems in the rest of the workers, thus when one worker goes down, the others are more likely to go down as well.
* Things like memory leaks, race conditions, unreleased resources, or deadlocks will become more apparent in chain reactions. Try to find these before they become big issues.
* Chain Reactions can be defended against by using *Bulkheads*.

#### Cascading Failures
* Similar to chain reactions
* When a failure in one layer of your system stack starts to cause failures in adjacent layers. For example, app code calls a database. The database goes dark. The app code tries to start a connection, fails, attempts to close the (nonexistant) connection, and that causes an unhandled exception to float up to the user.
* Commonly associated with exhausted resource pools and blocked threads and unbound retry attempts
* Cascading Failures can be defended against by using *Circuit breakers* and *Timeouts*

#### Users

A number of issues originate from users interacting with your system.

##### Traffic

* More users means more traffic, where your system will be stressed. It should be able to handle your heaviest load, and be able to scale.
* More users means more memory used on your servers, and machines with maxed out memory will behave more unpredictably.
* Write code that will allow objects to be easily garbaged collected. Learn how to do this in your language of choice. The author describes methods useful for Java.
* Given a enough people accessing your service, things that could happen in 1 in 10,000 times *will* happen.

##### Expensive Users

* If you're in eCommerce, having users checkout tends to be the most expensive operations your system goes through. Things like page browsing and search results can be cached and therefore cheap.
* If your system can be tested against its most expensive operations under load, then you can end up being in a good place for stability. The author says if you expect about a 2% conversion rate, then test between double to 5 times that amount. You could conceivably test at a 100% conversion rate, but *don't allocate prod resources according to that*. Your system will be far more expensive to maintain.

##### Unwanted Users

* Screen scrapers, impolite robots, trying to find best prices, frequently requesting deep links in your site without sending cookies or caching.
* Keep a robots.txt file on your site, robust enough to keep unwanted spiders away.
* If you get into a problem of constant scraping of your site, you can try blocking them at the CDN level or at IP level through reverse DNS. You can also define a Terms of Service and when scrapers violate it, sic your lawyers at them, if you got enough firepower with them.
* Don't try to be clever and "trap spiders". Remember that Search Engine will almost always have more bandwidth than you.

##### Malicious Users

* There's script kiddies
  + Common XSS and SQL Injection scripts on account creation and user input fields.
  + Brute force password cracking
  + DDoS using automated tools
* And then there's the pros.
  + APT with professional criminals and military/government forces.
  + Attacks based on long, hard-to-detect observation of your system and precise or custom attacks.
  + Attacks using a company insider,
  + Professional penetration testers
* Look for DDoS mitigation solutions from CDNs, network equipment, Web App firewalls.
* Proper monitoring solutions, logging, and alerts on your system will at least let you get a jump on when obvious attacks begin.

#### Blocked Threads

* Blocked threads can occur when the multiple requests are made to the same critical section and only one can be served at one time.
* Hard to test in development since it is rare that dev serves as many requests to the app that will be served in prod, and that sometimes the system has to be hit in a very specific sequence to generate a blocking issue.
* Use proven libraries when doing things like checking out connections, don't roll your own if you can.
* Beware of synchronizing domain objects when multiple threads are live in your app, rethink design.
* It may behoove you to test third-party libraries when unsure of its reliability under stress. Try hitting it with like 20 invocations in parallel and monitor any change in responsiveness. If the library breaks, you must take measures on your end to protect the library.
* Timeouts will help if connections begin to hang.

#### Attacks of Self denial
* When your marketing creates an offer too good to pass up, it blows up online, and you can't handle the traffic coming in. Be sure to know when business wants to create a special offer, then if you can anticipate what resources or sections will be hardest hit, you can plan accordingly.
* If you send out a special offer though email, only include links that lead to static landing pages for at least the first click

#### Scaling Effects
* Remember why we'll never see elephant sized spiders, weight scales with volume O(n^3) and leg strength O(n^2). This is sustainable at small values of n. Your software will crumble just the same if one resource doesn't scale as fast as others. Somethings will work in QA when servers are limited to one or two, but in prod, there are far more resources needed.
* Avoid Point-to-Point communication unless that is what your app needs to do. Leverage UDP broadcasts or TCP/UDP multicasts, Publish/subscribe messaging, or message queues.
* Beware of shared resources, common resources that be used underlying most of your architecture. See if in your stack layers, if one layer can scale, dependent layers should be able to scale too. If it is hard for underlying layers to scale, then that is a real problem. Try to account for the possibility that the shared resource can lock up or get slow.  

#### Unbalanced Capacities
* Let's assume your system has a limited set of hardware resources that can not dynamically create new instances of resources on demand. Unbalanced capacities mean some parts of the system are allocated too much resources for how often they are used, and others may be starving for resources that are used frequently. The front end can overwhelm the back end. Frontend should leverage circuit-breakers, backend should leverage handshaking for health, and critical services should be separated into bulkheads.
* Again, this problem may not appear in QA due to environment size. To counter this, the frontend should work in a test harness that can mimic a backend under heavy load, then should react gracefully. Load test your backend, make sure it leverages fail fast patterns.
* The author mentions checking the thread count of your front end processes versus your backend, and if there's a gross imbalance of threads, that's a problem (How relevant is this today?)

#### Slow Responses
* Beware of slow I/O, especially if for some reason, you're dealing with some hand-rolled protocol, or if it is blocking I/O.
* Slow responses can lead to users attempting to refresh the webpage, or unveil memory leak issues

#### SLA Inversion
* Your availability is only as good as the lowest availability of a (third party) service you rely on
* Decouple where you depend on services working so you can attempt to continue working if the service is down. Leverage circuit breakers that can notify ops when a service is down
* Be very specific in your SLA's! Craft your SLA's around sets of functionality your system provides. Any functionality you provide that depends on a third party, you can only provide a max availability of the third party (or your own service, whichever has the lowest availability). 

#### Unbounded Result Sets
* When querying for data, **always** have a limit on the number of records that can be returned. Provide some means of paging if you need more data than what is provided back.
* Try to get a prod-size amount of data into your system during development so you have a realistic idea if your system can handle it.

### Stability Patterns

#### Timeouts - code oriented
* Timeouts tell code to stop waiting if a response from a service or thread is taking long to complete, long enough that you suspect the answer will never come, or is longer than you're willing to wait.
* May be helpful to establish a class that handles making the connection, executing the query, and processing the result. May be helpful to have Circuit breaking incorporated into this class
* Waiting indefinitely is bad, returning some kind of response, failure included, is always better
* Learn if Connection classes used in your language/framework of choice have timeout components and handling to them.
* Immediately re-trying a timed out option could sometimes work, but more often will fail again. Consider queueing the work and re-trying after some significant time
* Timeouts can also help with large unbound return sets, but there are better ways of dealing with that
* This is similar to the *Fail Fast* pattern, where *Fail Fast* handles incoming requests that can't finish and *Timeout* handles outward requests that you don't think are going to finish.

#### Circuit Breakers - code oriented
* Circuit breakers stop operations from happening when a system is not in a healthy state. If 'open', any call of that operation will fail immediately saying this operation is down and needs attention. 'Closed' circuits are healthy. If too many failures occur or if manually flipped open, the circuit breaker flips open *and logs and notifies it changed*. After some time passes, the breaker can go to 'half-open' where it will retry the operation, and if it succeeds, it goes back to 'closed'
* Circuits can switch, say, if one operation times out, if connections are refused, maybe if there's some incompatible version differences, and these things happen repeatedly.
* Failure due to circuit breaker open should be a unique kind of exception, so code can handle it differently
* Ops team needs to have a means to monitor breakers, manually set and reset breakers, and have access to logs of state changes
* Protects system reliability at integration points

#### Bulkheads - architecturally oriented 
* On a ship, bulkheads are compartments that can be closed water tight in case the hull is breeched.
* Bulkheads in architecture separate servers from each other so that if one server goes down or can't serve properly, others which may have been dependent can continue working. If two different services depend on a common service, the common service can be made available into two pools, then each different service gets its own.
* One option is to separate critical services into a pool while non-critical can go into another
* The goal is to minimize impact of failure. What is the impact of a certain loss of capability, examine your system, see what makes sense to separate in terms of system boundaries
* At a CPU process level, having a process bound to a CPU core instead of hopping across all is an example of using the bulkhead idea
* Be aware of the needs of different services dependent on a common service that you bulkhead, there could be underuse of the service if one service is more demanding than the other, but they have the same size bulkhead pools

#### Steady State - ops oriented, deployment oriented
* Systems should not need to be fiddled with as part of its normal operation, as fiddling is a sign that there's something missed in creating the system. This includes cleaning up logs and purging old data.
* *Steady state* means that for every process that accumulates resources, there should be a process that prevents the overflow of that resource.
* Data purging - often neglected in first releases. Signs of this becoming a problem include increasing I/O rates and latency on the DB. Difficulties may include maintain referential integrity, and ensuring the app works still after old data is purged. If you must release data purging later, it's smart to take care of the most rapidly increasing data first.
* Old logs - remember to roll your logs! Many logging frameworks include this, find this in your choice of logging frameworks. Logs should never grow without having a size limit, regardless of where they're stored (they should always be stored outside of the prod system). Normally, logs from more than a week old are pretty uninteresting. If your framework doesn't have log rolling, or you have a legacy app, consider using something like `logrotate` or writing a script that runs purging old logs
* Memory cache - there needs to be a limit on the number of cache keys, and if cached items can change, there needs to be a way to invalidate/ refresh the cache, like using a time-based, least recently used, or working-set flushes.

#### Fail fast - code oriented
* Slow responses are worse than no response, and a slow failure is the worst of all. Always check for possible failures as early as possible.
* Do all your parameter validation before anything else, then verify and validate you can allocate all your needed resources before you do any business logic. This includes verifying things like db and endpoint connections
* Use different error handling means for System failures (like failing a db connection) versus App failures (like bad parameters that are ultimately user errors) so that any Circuit Breakers don't get tripped when the system is otherwise healthy

#### Handshaking - code oriented
* Handshaking really means a client asks a server if it is ready for a request, the server says yes or no, then the client behaves appropriately. This is a means for the server to throttle its workload.
* May rely on the use of healthchecks and heartbeats to servers. Say, a load balancer asks for healthchecks on app servers. The server may reply 'OK' so it can accept more work, or may say 'Service Unavailable' and then the load balancer won't give more work to the server
* Consider a healthcheck call as a part of your API you're writing, and using a handshake for any protocols you may develop

#### Test harness - development and testing oriented
* Because integration testing environments are difficult to maintain and is really only reliable for testing when everything is working correctly, it's useful to write pieces of software for testing that surround one component, and emulates all sorts of failures that could occur in the real world
* The bigger and scarier the scenarios you can put into the test harness, the better. Harness is meant as a controllable stress test to supplement other tests, like unit testing, qa, etc
* see page 126 for a list of failure ideas for a test harness
* encourages using low-level code to recreate all sorts of nonsense, think on all 7 layers of OSI
* Try having different ports set up to repeat different scenarios
* Log requests set to the harness, and what the harness is doing so you can repeat epic failures and know what happened

#### Decoupling middleware - architecture oriented
* Middleware/ enterprise application integrations help disparate systems talk to each other by letting each system talk to the middleware in the way that it wants to, then middleware translates that for the other.
* Supports decoupling by isolating system-specific call knowledge away from the core of each system.
* Synchronous systems are easier to understand, but far more bittle and could potentially lead to cascading system failures
* Asynchronous systems are more robust, may support storing messages in queues, but are may be harder to work with
* If you're in a position to make a decision about purchasing some piece of middleware for an enterprise level app, ***plan your system as much as you can in advance and wait till the last possible responsible moment to buy since this will be very costly to change***
* With that in mind, learn many system architectures so you can always be confident that your design will be the best fit for your app.


### Stability summary
  * 10 million page views a day for 3 years is over 500 billion, and there are 400 billion stars in the Milky Way. A bug in code that has astronomical chances of actually happening will definitely happen with the right amount of traffic
  * Remember that over 75% of projects get shut down before hitting prod, and the ones that do probably have some issues. If you fix enough problems in a buggy system, you'll look a hero, but if you design a system right from the beginning, it will probably be thankless, then users could complain it's slow. With that, update your capacity

